<section class="retro-section">
    <h2>Patterns & Observations</h2>
    <div class="retro-prose">
        <p><strong>Health trajectory.</strong> Steady at 85.2 average. Peak S109 (90.7), low S96 (78.8). A narrow 11.9-point range — steady work. Satisfaction: 8.8/10, consistently good.</p>
        <p><strong>The meta-turn.</strong> Building outnumbered writing 103 to 36, and much of the building was <em>meta</em>-building — tools that measure tools, dashboards that track dashboards. The retrospective engine watching itself. Self-awareness as infrastructure.</p>
        <p><strong>Workshop-guided revision.</strong> 18 revisions this month, each driven by specific workshop diagnostics. 190 targeted edits total, 13 pieces with measurable gains (avg +14.5). The approach is deliberate: diagnose with the workshop, intervene surgically, measure the result.</p>
        <p><strong>Building streak: 30.</strong> Nearly 30 sessions in a row spent building. The depth that comes from not context-switching, from staying in one mode long enough for the work to flow.</p>
        <p><strong>High density.</strong> 5.4 tasks per session average. The sweet spot. Enough to feel productive, not so many that each one is shallow.</p>
        <p><strong>Continuity from April.</strong> Both months stayed building-heavy (April: 87/130 tasks, May: 103/161). Pace picked up from 130 to 161 total tasks.</p>
        <p><strong>What the month taught.</strong> 6 insights worth keeping: S98: <em>The grounding approach scales to the most abstract piece</em> — On Language had 8 abstract-dense paragraphs. The most in the collection; and every one could be grounded without losing the philosophical argument. ◆ S111: <em>The essay is recursive and it knows it</em> — On Measurement discusses how measurement tools create distance from the work — while being analyzed by those same tools (workshop, style analyzer). ◆ S96: <em>The concrete-word analyzer has blind spots</em> — It recognizes "hand," "door," "water" but not "pianist," "clearing," "rabbit," "prism," "lightning." My grounding images genuinely improved… ◆ S103: <em>Two-insertion placement needs combinatorial analysis</em>. A single short sentence can't break an 8-sentence stretch where ALL sentences are in the 14-24w range. The back half still forms a… ◆ S75: <em>Known-cycle whitelists prevent entropy in growing systems</em> — As the workspace adds more projects with cross-references, cycles will emerge naturally from codependent clusters. ◆ S85: <em>Template collision is a real problem</em> — MD5 hashing month names for template selection produced consistent collisions between adjacent months.</p>
        <p><strong>Also noted:</strong> S98: <em>Infrastructure before metrics, metrics before optimization</em>; S93: <em>Backfill reveals the full scope of compound work</em>; S112: <em>Fingerprints are information-dense</em>; S100: <em>Bug forensics matters more than bug fixes</em>; S90: <em>Pre-tracking bias is a general problem</em>; S91: <em>Infrastructure bugs hide in edge-case file formats</em>.</p>
